{"slug": "magus", "root": "magus", "category": "profession", "gloss": "a master mage (Latin/Persian magi)", "definition": "A magus is a master magician of the loftiest, most learned kind — the philosopher-mage who reads the hidden correspondences of the cosmos and works within them. Where an ordinary conjurer or enchanter performs an operation, the magus commands a whole worldview, mediating between the terrestrial and the celestial. The word keeps the hieratic dignity of the Persian priest-astrologer.", "history": "The word is Latin *magus*, from Greek *magos*, from Old Persian *maguš* — originally a Persian priest and astrologer, as the Renaissance well knew, though the claim that *magus* simply means 'wise man' in Persian is a repeated commonplace more than a verified fact. Its ambivalence was fixed early: the New Testament sets the wonder-working Simon Magus against the apostles, making 'magus' a name for the false wonder-worker as readily as the wise one. The rehabilitating turn came with Ficino, Pico, and Agrippa, whom scholars like Frances Yates cast as the exalted 'Renaissance Magus' — a co-creator ordering nature by knowledge. Magic uses the word for its most elevated practitioners.", "def_sources": [{"label": "Paola Zambelli, Astrology and Magic from the Medieval Latin and Islamic World to Renaissance Europe", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://www.routledge.com/Astrology-and-Magic-from-the-Medieval-Latin-and-Islamic-World-to-Renaissance-Europe-Theories-and-Approaches/Zambelli/p/book/9781409425144", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "A collection of the author's essays tracing how astrology (reading the stars to predict events) passed from Islamic and Latin medieval scholars into the Renaissance, and how astrologers actually worked as court advisors and public intellectuals, not just armchair theorists."}, {"label": "Yates, Giordano Bruno and the Hermetic Tradition", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/G/bo3639032.html", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "A classic study arguing that the Renaissance philosopher Giordano Bruno, burned at the stake in 1600, was driven less by early modern science than by \"Hermeticism\" -- a set of ancient-seeming magical and mystical teachings he believed held the secret key to controlling nature."}, {"label": "Etymonline, s.v. magus (Greek magos ← Old Persian maguš)", "where": "Etymology reference"}], "commentary": "For a generation the *magus* was a hero. Frances Yates cast the Renaissance Magus — Ficino, Pico, Agrippa, Bruno — as a bold new operator on nature whose confidence helped birth modern science. Critics have since dismantled the too-clean portrait: Håkan Håkansson calls the picture of Dee as a 'Hermetic magus' 'much too simplistic,' restoring his debt to Aristotle and medieval philosophy. Behind the honorific stands its shadow twin, Simon Magus, the New Testament's false wonder-worker; Kieckhefer and Edward Peters show how the Christian construction of 'the magician' fixed the word's ambivalence from the start. The field now reads the magus as a contested label, not a movement.", "commentary_sources": [{"label": "Frances Yates, Giordano Bruno and the Hermetic Tradition", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://press.uchicago.edu/ucp/books/book/chicago/G/bo3639032.html", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "A classic study arguing that the Renaissance philosopher Giordano Bruno, burned at the stake in 1600, was driven less by early modern science than by \"Hermeticism\" -- a set of ancient-seeming magical and mystical teachings he believed held the secret key to controlling nature."}, {"label": "Håkan Håkansson, Seeing the Word: John Dee and Renaissance Occultism", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://www.lunduniversity.lu.se/lup/publication/bd3769a7-e1b2-4166-b92f-d6a07428d138", "url_kind": "catalog", "abstract": "A doctoral thesis arguing that John Dee's strange mix of interests -- grammar, the Kabbalah, astronomy, alchemy, and math -- were not scattered hobbies but one connected project: recovering a lost perfect language Dee believed could unlock both nature's secrets and God's truth."}, {"label": "Edward Peters, The Magician, the Witch, and the Law", "where": "Renaissance magic (PDF)", "url": "https://www.pennpress.org/9780812211016/the-magician-the-witch-and-the-law/", "url_kind": "publisher", "abstract": "Peters traces how medieval Europe's view of magic changed over time: early on, magic was treated as a learnable (if suspect) skill, but law and church authorities gradually redefined it as heresy, turning practitioners once seen as skilled specialists into criminals who could be prosecuted as witches."}], "is_keyword": false, "etymology": {"origin": "Latin magus ← Greek magos ← Old Persian maguš", "first": "1510s (pl. magi much earlier, in scripture)", "note": "Same root as mage; ‘magus’ keeps the loftier, hieratic flavour of the Persian priest-astrologer.", "hook": "The three magi were astrologers, not kings.", "lang": "Persian"}, "essay": null, "sources": ["Etymonline (Douglas Harper)", "Wiktionary", "classical lexica (Lewis & Short, LSJ, Bosworth–Toller)", "Ted's historical-magic DBs (WitchcraftStudiesDB, AgrippaDOP, MedievalMagicDB)"], "stats": {"flavor_total": 3, "oracle_total": 0, "in_flavor_cards": 3, "in_oracle_cards": 0, "name_match_count": 31, "by_variant": {"magus": 3}, "first_year": 2006, "colors": {"G": 6, "U": 6, "C": 6, "B": 6, "W": 5, "R": 5}, "by_year": {"2006": 2, "2007": 4, "2008": 1, "2011": 1, "2013": 1, "2014": 7, "2017": 2, "2018": 2, "2020": 4, "2021": 3, "2022": 2, "2023": 1, "2024": 1, "2025": 1}}, "cards": [{"id": "d547275a-bc31-4c05-9db3-27b5efe47bb1", "name": "Magus of the Jar", "set": "TSP", "set_name": "Time Spiral", "released": "2006-10-06", "type_line": "Creature — Human Wizard", "rarity": "rare", "colors": ["U"], "img_small": "https://cards.scryfall.io/small/front/3/1/31961041-a9e6-4d96